<sec>
<st>
Effects</st>
<p>

The incident temporarily shut down the entire refinery and caused oil prices to increase. Damage was caused to the nearby villages of <site wordnetid="108651247" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../596/1848596.xml">
North</link></site>
 and <site wordnetid="108651247" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../295/2654295.xml">
South Killingholme</link></site>
 as well as the nearby town of Immingham - mainly doors being blown from their hinges and windows being blown in.</p>

</sec>
<sec>
<st>
HSE investigation</st>
<p>

<company wordnetid="108058098" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../730/319730.xml">
ConocoPhillips</link></company>
, as the company is now known, was investigated and subsequently fined £895,000 and ordered to pay £218,854 costs by the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../308/361308.xml">
Health and Safety Executive</link> for failing to effectively monitor the degradation of the refinery's pipework. The company pleaded guilty to these charges in court and has since implemented a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../983/5985983.xml">
Risk Based Inspection</link> programme.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref></p>

